{
  "schema_version": 1,
  "name": "Pitch Gravity",
  "mood": "Aether",
  "engines": ["OpenSky"],
  "author": "Guru Bin",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "description": "Gravity as timbre. PitchEnvAmount at 0.8 with a sharp decay (0.15 seconds) means every note begins above itself and falls to pitch. The attack feels like a statement just before the speaker commits to the word. Each note rises then settles — the pitch envelope is the physics of falling light. Wide unison (5 voices, 0.03 detune) creates mass without losing coherence. The fall is the melody.",
  "tags": ["opensky", "pitch-envelope", "gravity", "transient", "aether", "guru-bin", "falling", "expressive"],
  "tier": "transcendental",
  "guru_bin": {
    "retreat": "OPENSKY — Above the Cloud Line",
    "retreat_date": "2026-03-19",
    "vol": "Transcendental Vol 1",
    "scripture": [
      "Verse 9: Pitch Envelope as Physics — pitchEnvAmount above 0.6 makes gravity audible",
      "Verse 3: The Fall Is the Melody — a pitch transient with fast decay changes melody's relationship to time",
      "Discovery 2: Supersaw Fallacy — unisonCount=5 at detune=0.03 for mass with coherence"
    ],
    "revelation": null,
    "god": null,
    "flock_note": "The Guru played a scale with pitchEnvAmount=0.8, decay=0.15. Each note arrived from above. The melody existed in two registers simultaneously: where it began (high) and where it settled (the note). Listeners heard a chord when only one note was played. The fall was the upper voice. Physics, not synthesis, wrote the harmony.",
    "diagnosis": "Pitch Gravity uses pitchEnvAmount=0.8 with pitchEnvDecay=0.15 — a sharp rise followed by rapid settling. The resulting transient gives each note a falling quality, like catching something thrown from above. Five unison voices at tight 0.03 detune provide mass without smear. Medium shimmer (0.4) adds tail without obscuring the pitch mechanics."
  },
